ARP shows the mapping between IP addresses and MAC addresses on your local network. Use it to spot duplicate IPs or to find the hardware address of a neighbour:

ARP table

arp –a or /a

ARP -A


--------------------------------------------------------------------

Tests network connectivity to a host or IP address

ping <hostname_or_ip>

Add -t to ping continuously until you press Ctrl + C — great for watching a flaky connection over time. PING -t 192.168.1.1

Other useful switches: 
​•​         -n count — number of echo requests to send. ​
•​         -l size — buffer size for the request (test for fragmentation issues). 
​•​         -a — resolve addresses to hostnames. 
​•​         -4 / -6 — force IPv4 or IPv6.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TRACERT (trace route) maps every router between your machine and the destination, showing the round-trip time at each hop.
Traces the route packets to reach a destination

tracert <hostname_or_ip>

TRACERT google.com

PATHPING — TRACERT + Statistics
PATHPING combines TRACERT and PING into a single report.

PATHPING google.com


