Queries DNS servers to resolve domain names or IP addresses
NSLOOKUP queries a DNS server for the IP address of a hostname. The first line of the answer tells you which DNS server replied — useful to confirm that your machine is asking the resolver you expect.

nslookup <hostname>


---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Displays active TCP/IP connections, listening ports, and network statistics.
NETSTAT lists active TCP and UDP connections. Run it on its own for a clean list of conversations in progress:

netstat [-a] [-n] [-o]

Combine -A and -N to display all sockets, including listening ones, and skip the hostname lookup (faster, and exposes ports you might want to investigate).

NETSTAT -AN

Other handy switches: 
​•​         -O — show the owning process ID for each connection. ​
•​         -B — show the executable name behind each connection (run as admin). ​
•​         -R — display the routing table. 
​•​         -S — protocol statistics.




